Vladimir Putin and the Risk of a Third World War
San Francisco — On February 24, Russia's invasion of Ukraine marked the beginning of the third world war that could potentially destroy our civilization.
Before the invasion, Russian President Vladimir Putin and Chinese President Xi Jinping held a lengthy meeting on February 4 — that day marked the beginning of the Chinese Lunar New Year celebrations and the Beijing Winter Olympic Games.
After the meeting, the two issued a carefully drafted 5,000-word document announcing the establishment of a close partnership between the two countries.
This document is stronger than any treaty and certainly requires detailed negotiations in advance.
I was shocked that Xi seemed to have fully entrusted Putin with invading and launching the war in Ukraine.
He believes that the confirmation of his becoming a lifelong ruler in the second half of this year is merely a formality, and he is certainly confident about it.
After concentrating all power in his own hands, Xi carefully devised a plan to elevate himself to the level of Mao Zedong and Deng Xiaoping.
With Xi's support, Putin set about realizing his lifelong dream in an unimaginably brutal manner.
A 70-year-old Putin feels that if he wants to leave a significant mark in Russian history, it's either now or never.
But his view of Russia's role in the world is distorted.
He seems to believe that the Russian people need a tsar who can be blindly followed.
This system is the exact opposite of a democratic society, and this vision has distorted the emotionally sensitive souls of the Russian people to an extreme degree.
In my childhood, I had frequent contact with Russian soldiers who occupied Hungary in 1945.
I know that if you ask them for something, they will share their last piece of bread with you.
Later, in the early 1980s, I launched what I called my political charity work.
At first, I established a foundation in my homeland, Hungary, and later actively participated in activities that contributed to the dissolution of the Soviet Empire.
When Mikhail Gorbachev came to power in 1985, this process had already begun.
I also established a foundation in Russia, and later in each of the newly independent republics.
In Ukraine, even before it became an independent country, I established a foundation.
I also visited China in 1984 and became the first foreigner allowed to establish a foundation (I closed this foundation in 1989, shortly before the Tiananmen Square massacre).
I don't personally know Putin, but I have closely followed his rise and fully understand his ruthless personality.
He reduced Chechnya's capital, Grozny, to rubble, and now he threatens to do the same to Kyiv, the capital of Ukraine.
Putin was once a shrewd KGB agent, but he has seemed to change in recent years.
He seems to have lost touch with reality because he has formed a fixed notion.
There is no doubt that he misjudged the situation in Ukraine.
He had assumed that the Ukrainian people who spoke Russian would welcome Russian soldiers with open arms, but in reality, they were no different from the Ukrainian-speaking population.
Faced with the seemingly one-sided possibility, the Ukrainian people still carried out an incredible act of courageous resistance.
In July 2021, Putin published a long article claiming that Russians and Ukrainians are actually one people, and that Ukrainians had been misled by new Nazi agitators.
Because Kyiv is the original site of the Russian Orthodox Church, the first part of his argument is not without historical basis.
But in the second part of his argument, it was Putin who was misled.
He should have been more aware of the facts.
Many Ukrainians fought bravely during the Euromaidan protests that erupted in 2014.
The 2014 events made him extremely angry.
But when ordered to attack their Ukrainian brothers, the Russian army performed poorly.
The deeply rooted corruption within the Ministry of Defense also played a significant role in this poor performance.
But Putin not only did not blame himself but seemed to have gone mad.
He has resolved to punish Ukraine for opposing him, and his actions seem to be without any restraint.
He committed the entire Russian army to battle and disregarded all combat rules, especially bombarding civilian populations without distinction.
Numerous hospitals were attacked, and the power grid supplying electricity to the Chernobyl Nuclear Power Plant, which is currently under Russian control, was also destroyed.
In the besieged Mariupol, as many as 400,000 people have been without water and food for nearly a week.
Russia is likely to lose this war.
The United States and the European Union are both delivering defensive weapons to Ukraine while simultaneously trying to purchase Russian-made MiG fighter jets that Ukrainian pilots know how to operate.
These could change the entire situation.
No matter the outcome, Putin has created a miracle in strengthening European resolve and unity.
At the same time, Xi seems to have realized that Putin has strayed from the right path.
On March 8, after Chinese Foreign Minister Wang Yi firmly asserted that Sino-Russian friendship remains "as solid as a rock," Xi called French President Emmanuel Macron and German Chancellor Olaf Scholz, expressing his support for their peacekeeping efforts.
To avoid a humanitarian crisis, he hopes to maintain maximum restraint during the war.
Whether Putin will accommodate Xi's wishes remains far from certain.
We can only hope that Putin and Xi will be removed from power before they destroy our civilization.
